@yashu-seth This raises ambiguity because in docstring you have written 
>list or array-like

We have allowed for all array like structures in all places, (though allowing dictionary do raises some doubts in my mind) but sets, tuples and np.array should be allowed. For eg user can use set in case of large number of variables to keep variable name distinct. I my views we cannot really presume things like this. Also you should also check for distinct variable names to avoid ambiguous results later which can be hard to debug later.

I'm actually not sure if removing elements from an `unordered_map` is allowed to change the iterator order or not. If it doesn't, then you would not even go through all the elements. And if it does, chances are someone may get confused about the same thing, so you may want to avoid this for that reason. :)

I think you could just do the following, though for cases where the above isn't an issue, the most "C++" way would be to return an iterator that points past the erased element from `remove_fetch_request`:

```
while (!state->fetch_requests.empty()) {
	remove_fetch_request(state->fetch_requests.begin()->second);
}
```
